<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-10-02T02:34:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-10-02T02:34:00-05:00" n="751" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d751">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/2754: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The President of the Technical Board</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Stevens</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Harbin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-10-02T16:00:00+08:26"><hi rend="italic">October 2,
                                        1922—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 3—10:13
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>It seems to be well established that the Moscow envoy extraordinary now
                            in Peking will shortly have a conference with the Chinese Government to
                            dispose of Chinese Eastern Railway between themselves.</p>
                        <p>The Chinese Government assuming authority under section 3, Radio
                            Resolution, Washington Conference,<note n="94" xml:id="d751fn94"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_293">p.
                                293</ref>.</note> has seized Russian radio station at Harbin.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stevens</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>